WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.888
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:04.860 --> 00:00:07.360
JAIME GREEN: Please welcome to
the stage Senator Al Franken.

00:00:07.360 --> 00:00:11.053
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:11.053 --> 00:00:12.031
AL FRANKEN: Thank you.

00:00:12.031 --> 00:00:13.196
Thank you.

00:00:13.196 --> 00:00:13.987
JAIME GREEN: Hello.

00:00:13.987 --> 00:00:15.195
AL FRANKEN: Thank you, Jaime.

00:00:15.195 --> 00:00:16.432
JAIME GREEN: Welcome.

00:00:16.432 --> 00:00:17.910
AL FRANKEN: Thank you.

00:00:17.910 --> 00:00:20.580
JAIME GREEN: I'd love to start
by talking about what inspired

00:00:20.580 --> 00:00:22.720
you to write this book.

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:26.660
A lot of the book is sort of
timeless political memoir.

00:00:26.660 --> 00:00:28.620
We get your childhood
and your career

00:00:28.620 --> 00:00:30.270
before the Senate and all that.

00:00:30.270 --> 00:00:32.520
But as it gets closer
to the current day,

00:00:32.520 --> 00:00:38.980
it starts to feel kind of urgent
and specific to our moment.

00:00:38.980 --> 00:00:42.995
And so I was curious when you
decided to write this book.

00:00:42.995 --> 00:00:45.120
AL FRANKEN: When I decided
to write this book was--

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:51.330
this book is sort
of about answering

00:00:51.330 --> 00:00:55.446
the question I get asked
the most, which is,

00:00:55.446 --> 00:00:58.950
is being a United States
senator as much fun

00:00:58.950 --> 00:01:01.620
as working on
"Saturday Night Live"?

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:05.250
And the answer to that is no.

00:01:05.250 --> 00:01:07.710
Why would it be?

00:01:07.710 --> 00:01:09.540
But it's the best
job I've ever had,

00:01:09.540 --> 00:01:13.450
because you get to
improve people's lives.

00:01:13.450 --> 00:01:18.510
And so-- and a lot
of this is also

00:01:18.510 --> 00:01:24.420
about the tension of having
been a comedian and a satirist

00:01:24.420 --> 00:01:27.960
pretty much all my life, and
then making this transition.

00:01:27.960 --> 00:01:31.800
That's the question I
get asked second most,

00:01:31.800 --> 00:01:34.140
how did I make that transition?

00:01:34.140 --> 00:01:38.340
And I felt free to
start writing this

00:01:38.340 --> 00:01:42.840
after I was re-elected,
because my first election was

00:01:42.840 --> 00:01:45.270
a 312 vote margin.

00:01:45.270 --> 00:01:46.530
And we had a recount.

00:01:46.530 --> 00:01:49.500
We had a legal proceeding.

00:01:49.500 --> 00:01:57.960
So my wife and I were
going to have a vacation,

00:01:57.960 --> 00:02:01.560
six days up in a lodge
in Northern Minnesota.

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:04.440
She was in Washington
with her grandchildren,

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:07.995
and she got sick.

00:02:07.995 --> 00:02:09.870
And we were going to go
to Africa immediately

00:02:09.870 --> 00:02:13.320
after that vacation on a codel,
a congressional delegation

00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:17.190
trip, so she wanted to
just rest up for that.

00:02:17.190 --> 00:02:20.490
So I ended up in a
cabin for six days.

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:24.971
And I had threatened to
myself to write about this,

00:02:24.971 --> 00:02:26.220
so I started writing about it.

00:02:26.220 --> 00:02:27.700
And I was worried
that, you know,

00:02:27.700 --> 00:02:29.700
it would just become "The
Shining" or something.

00:02:29.700 --> 00:02:31.350
[LAUGHTER]

00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:32.810
But it didn't.

00:02:32.810 --> 00:02:34.890
It was a lot of
fun, and it actually

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:37.710
helped me think about
being a senator.

00:02:37.710 --> 00:02:40.230
And so I try to tell
people how I make

00:02:40.230 --> 00:02:43.750
this transition, how I made it.

00:02:43.750 --> 00:02:47.100
It had its hairy moments.

00:02:47.100 --> 00:02:50.220
That first campaign
was very ugly.

00:02:50.220 --> 00:02:56.970
They took every thing that I had
ever said or written in comedy

00:02:56.970 --> 00:02:59.280
and put it through this--

00:02:59.280 --> 00:03:01.220
you'd be interested
in this machine.

00:03:01.220 --> 00:03:03.780
It's called the dehumanizer.

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:06.810
And it had a lot of technology
from Silicon Valley.

00:03:06.810 --> 00:03:11.880
And what it does is it
decontextualizes anything

00:03:11.880 --> 00:03:16.300
you ever wrote as a joke, and
just takes out all the irony,

00:03:16.300 --> 00:03:18.540
hyperbole-- anything
you've done--

00:03:18.540 --> 00:03:23.040
and leaves it as something
that you can attack.

00:03:23.040 --> 00:03:25.380
And they did that.

00:03:25.380 --> 00:03:33.440
For example, I wrote
a piece, I don't

00:03:33.440 --> 00:03:38.280
know, around 1999 or
2000, about the internet

00:03:38.280 --> 00:03:42.270
and how parents should kind
of monitor what their kids are

00:03:42.270 --> 00:03:43.230
doing on the internet.

00:03:43.230 --> 00:03:48.360
And I wrote what I think is
a very conservative joke.

00:03:48.360 --> 00:03:54.570
I said that, you know,
the internet is great.

00:03:54.570 --> 00:03:59.670
My son uses the internet
to do a sixth grade

00:03:59.670 --> 00:04:02.010
report on beastiality.

00:04:02.010 --> 00:04:09.420
And he downloaded a
lot of great images.

00:04:09.420 --> 00:04:12.990
And the kids in the class just
loved them, because you know,

00:04:12.990 --> 00:04:15.840
at that age they're
just sponges.

00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:20.610
And so that was turned
into an ad which is,

00:04:20.610 --> 00:04:23.750
Al Franken jokes
about beastiality.

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:29.240
It kind of comes from infinity
and then goes through your--

00:04:29.240 --> 00:04:29.895
the drone.

00:04:29.895 --> 00:04:32.340
[DEEP VOICE] Al Franken.

00:04:32.340 --> 00:04:33.270
You know?

00:04:33.270 --> 00:04:35.940
And so there was a lot of that.

00:04:35.940 --> 00:04:38.130
So I won by 312 votes.

00:04:38.130 --> 00:04:41.250
And I felt that the
people of Minnesota

00:04:41.250 --> 00:04:43.620
deserved to know I was
there for a serious purpose.

00:04:43.620 --> 00:04:49.600
So I built my own
dehumanizer, my staff, and--

00:04:49.600 --> 00:04:51.285
[LAUGHTER]

00:04:53.720 --> 00:04:57.967
I kind of showed people,
Minnesotans especially,

00:04:57.967 --> 00:05:00.300
that I was going to be a
workhorse and not a show horse.

00:05:00.300 --> 00:05:02.180
And I did that.

00:05:02.180 --> 00:05:06.870
I won re-election by a
very comfortable amount.

00:05:06.870 --> 00:05:12.600
And it's freed me up to be
a workhorse with a sense

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:14.370
of humor, to be funny again.

00:05:14.370 --> 00:05:15.890
JAIME GREEN: Yeah.

00:05:15.890 --> 00:05:20.300
Before we go into talking
about your work in the Senate,

00:05:20.300 --> 00:05:23.690
I do want to ask one
question about your comedy.

00:05:23.690 --> 00:05:28.347
Because you move pretty quickly
through your "SNL" and comedy

00:05:28.347 --> 00:05:29.430
writing years in the book.

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:34.430
But one thing that really struck
me was you write about one

00:05:34.430 --> 00:05:37.560
of your most famous
characters, Stuart Smalley,

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:42.180
who actually is this ridiculous
mockery of a character

00:05:42.180 --> 00:05:44.180
in a lot of ways but
actually came from a really

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:45.292
sincere inspiration.

00:05:45.292 --> 00:05:46.000
AL FRANKEN: Yeah.

00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:48.350
I don't think of him as
a mockery of a character.

00:05:51.470 --> 00:05:54.950
Basically, what happens-- and
I talk about in the campaign,

00:05:54.950 --> 00:05:56.800
my wife Franni--

00:05:56.800 --> 00:06:02.060
I was being attacked all the
time through those kind of ads.

00:06:02.060 --> 00:06:06.650
And she is an alcoholic.

00:06:06.650 --> 00:06:08.960
She's a recovering alcoholic.

00:06:08.960 --> 00:06:14.180
There was a period where
it was tough, obviously,

00:06:14.180 --> 00:06:18.080
on her and on our marriage.

00:06:18.080 --> 00:06:21.140
But she talked about how
I stuck it out with her.

00:06:21.140 --> 00:06:23.750
And she wanted to talk
about my character.

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:24.980
And she did an ad.

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:27.950
She sat down with
Mandy Grunwald,

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:32.300
who was our media consultant,
and did a beautiful ad.

00:06:32.300 --> 00:06:36.140
It's in a chapter called
"Franni Saves the Campaign."

00:06:36.140 --> 00:06:43.460
And she just wanted to talk
about how not only did I

00:06:43.460 --> 00:06:48.680
stand with her and
support her, but also I

00:06:48.680 --> 00:06:54.590
wrote a couple of
movies about this,

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:57.890
one called "A Man Loves a Woman"
with Meg Ryan and Andy Garcia.

00:06:57.890 --> 00:06:59.780
She wanted to know
that people did this.

00:06:59.780 --> 00:07:05.630
She said something in the ad
that just made me cry and made

00:07:05.630 --> 00:07:09.740
Chuck Schumer cry,
which is actually easier

00:07:09.740 --> 00:07:10.970
to do than you might think.

00:07:10.970 --> 00:07:12.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:15.620 --> 00:07:18.200
And in this ad, they
showed pictures of us

00:07:18.200 --> 00:07:19.370
and our kids and stuff.

00:07:19.370 --> 00:07:25.790
She said, how can a mother of
two such beautiful children

00:07:25.790 --> 00:07:27.830
be an alcoholic?

00:07:27.830 --> 00:07:35.090
And it spoke to the
shame that a lot of women

00:07:35.090 --> 00:07:38.240
feel and alcoholics feel.

00:07:38.240 --> 00:07:44.000
And it just touched a nerve.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:47.360
An anchor at the CBS
affiliate in Minneapolis

00:07:47.360 --> 00:07:51.230
said, this is the best
political ad of the year

00:07:51.230 --> 00:07:54.800
because it's actually an
ad that could help people.

00:07:54.800 --> 00:08:02.060
And two days after the ad ran,
we had a debate in a gymnasium.

00:08:02.060 --> 00:08:04.845
The place was jammed full,
and people on the floor

00:08:04.845 --> 00:08:05.720
and in the bleachers.

00:08:05.720 --> 00:08:09.140
When she entered the room,
she got a standing ovation.

00:08:09.140 --> 00:08:12.190
And I wouldn't have
won without that ad.

00:08:12.190 --> 00:08:17.210
I would have lost
by a lot, I imagine.

00:08:17.210 --> 00:08:21.830
So during that time, during
that period of our lives,

00:08:21.830 --> 00:08:23.420
I was at "SNL" and
I started going

00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:25.490
to Al-Anon, which is
for family members

00:08:25.490 --> 00:08:26.960
and friends of alcoholics.

00:08:26.960 --> 00:08:29.697
And I learned a
lot about myself.

00:08:29.697 --> 00:08:31.280
And one of the things
I learned, which

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:34.580
I'm kind of
embarrassed to say, is

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:37.309
that I learned in
Al-Anon meetings

00:08:37.309 --> 00:08:41.270
that you can learn stuff from
people who at first blush

00:08:41.270 --> 00:08:44.059
don't seem smart.

00:08:44.059 --> 00:08:48.200
And my parents have always
emphasized education,

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:50.210
and you learn from
people who are

00:08:50.210 --> 00:08:53.060
educated and smarter than you.

00:08:53.060 --> 00:08:54.920
My dad didn't
graduate high school,

00:08:54.920 --> 00:08:57.510
so it was very important.

00:08:57.510 --> 00:09:02.060
And there was a guy who Stuart
was a little model laughter who

00:09:02.060 --> 00:09:04.970
said that the higher
power had put an apartment

00:09:04.970 --> 00:09:06.340
in his life one week.

00:09:06.340 --> 00:09:08.050
And I just went, ugh.

00:09:08.050 --> 00:09:10.700
It was here in New York.

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:12.440
And the next week,
he said something

00:09:12.440 --> 00:09:16.890
that just hit me so hard that
was about his experience.

00:09:16.890 --> 00:09:20.780
And so I made a character
who was very vulnerable

00:09:20.780 --> 00:09:24.200
and kind of at first
blush an idiot,

00:09:24.200 --> 00:09:28.920
but to try to explain
what recovery was.

00:09:28.920 --> 00:09:32.960
And so that's where
Stuart Smalley was from.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:33.710
JAIME GREEN: Yeah.

00:09:37.490 --> 00:09:42.640
So much of your comedy career
can be defined as satire,

00:09:42.640 --> 00:09:45.050
as a satirist.

00:09:45.050 --> 00:09:47.940
What's sort of the
impulse behind that?

00:09:47.940 --> 00:09:50.630
Because with Stuart, you were
trying to really communicate

00:09:50.630 --> 00:09:51.980
something sincere.

00:09:51.980 --> 00:09:54.290
AL FRANKEN: Yeah.

00:09:54.290 --> 00:09:56.400
I've done really stupid comedy--

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:04.820
you know, Belushi as Liz Taylor
choking on a chicken bone.

00:10:04.820 --> 00:10:06.620
Julia Child bleeding to death.

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:11.070
So I've done all kinds.

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:14.000
But I'd always done
political satire.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:23.610
And it really comes from very,
very early when I was young,

00:10:23.610 --> 00:10:25.660
the civil rights
movement was happening.

00:10:25.660 --> 00:10:31.450
And my dad, we watched the
news while we ate dinner

00:10:31.450 --> 00:10:32.866
on tray tables.

00:10:32.866 --> 00:10:33.990
My mom made a great dinner.

00:10:33.990 --> 00:10:36.400
It wasn't a TV dinner.

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:37.750
It was a really nice dinner.

00:10:37.750 --> 00:10:40.330
But we would watch the news.

00:10:40.330 --> 00:10:43.530
This was during the
civil rights struggle.

00:10:43.530 --> 00:10:48.990
And when sheriffs would put fire
hoses and billy clubs and dogs

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:53.220
on demonstrators, my dad
would point to the TV and say,

00:10:53.220 --> 00:10:55.770
no Jew can be for this.

00:10:55.770 --> 00:10:57.930
No Jew can be for this.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:03.570
And that was a very big lesson
for us, for me and my brother,

00:11:03.570 --> 00:11:08.460
about justice, and
why that matters.

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:10.800
And it's one of the reasons--

00:11:10.800 --> 00:11:13.210
actually, my dad
was a Republican.

00:11:13.210 --> 00:11:16.860
But when Barry Goldwater voted
against the civil rights bill

00:11:16.860 --> 00:11:23.550
and was the nominee, he became
a Democrat and stuck with that.

00:11:23.550 --> 00:11:27.050
So we lost the South because
of the civil rights bill,

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:28.140
but we gained my dad--

00:11:28.140 --> 00:11:30.864
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:30.864 --> 00:11:31.920
--and me.

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:36.880
And so I always
cared about politics

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:39.900
and I always wrote
political satire.

00:11:39.900 --> 00:11:42.930
And I'm very proud
of the work that I

00:11:42.930 --> 00:11:45.530
did in satire on the show.

00:11:45.530 --> 00:11:46.500
I write about this.

00:11:46.500 --> 00:11:49.320
Jim Downey is a guy
I wrote a lot with.

00:11:49.320 --> 00:11:52.450
He was a very
thoughtful conservative.

00:11:52.450 --> 00:11:54.450
I like to think I'm a
thoughtful progressive.

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:56.500
We did not feel that
the job of the show

00:11:56.500 --> 00:11:58.840
was to have a political bias.

00:11:58.840 --> 00:12:00.510
We felt the job of
the show was to do

00:12:00.510 --> 00:12:04.580
well-observed political satire.

00:12:04.580 --> 00:12:06.020
And Jim and the thing.

00:12:06.020 --> 00:12:09.870
It was, we want to reward
people for knowing stuff

00:12:09.870 --> 00:12:12.580
but not punish them
for not knowing stuff.

00:12:12.580 --> 00:12:19.170
So I think we wrote very well
observed, intelligent satire

00:12:19.170 --> 00:12:20.602
that everyone enjoyed.

00:12:20.602 --> 00:12:21.930
JAIME GREEN: Yeah.

00:12:21.930 --> 00:12:26.370
You mentioned earlier the
dehumanizer of the campaign,

00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:29.490
and then bringing that into
your own work in the Senate

00:12:29.490 --> 00:12:31.410
and focusing on--

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:33.910
AL FRANKEN: I'll give you an
example of the dehumanizer when

00:12:33.910 --> 00:12:37.020
I'm in the Senate.

00:12:37.020 --> 00:12:43.464
When the Supreme Court voted
5-4 on marriage equality,

00:12:43.464 --> 00:12:44.880
I thought that was
a big day and I

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:47.790
wanted to put out a
press release saying,

00:12:47.790 --> 00:12:51.495
I congratulate the Court
for making this decision.

00:12:54.660 --> 00:12:57.740
Actually, it was going
to be, Senator Franken

00:12:57.740 --> 00:13:01.840
is very happy with
this court's decision

00:13:01.840 --> 00:13:06.070
allowing everybody to
marry the person they love,

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:11.880
but Senator Franken felt
that Justice Scalia's dissent

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:13.471
was very gay.

00:13:13.471 --> 00:13:16.838
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:20.350 --> 00:13:21.790
My team said no.

00:13:21.790 --> 00:13:22.972
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:22.972 --> 00:13:23.824
JAIME GREEN: Really?

00:13:23.824 --> 00:13:24.535
AL FRANKEN: Yeah.

00:13:24.535 --> 00:13:25.660
No, you can't put that out.

00:13:25.660 --> 00:13:27.750
Now, this was after I
had won re-election.

00:13:27.750 --> 00:13:30.870
So I thought, oh, come on.

00:13:30.870 --> 00:13:34.510
And so we didn't put that out.

00:13:34.510 --> 00:13:36.040
But I got it in the book.

00:13:36.040 --> 00:13:37.550
It's in the book.

00:13:37.550 --> 00:13:40.690
So there's a lot of stuff
in the book that didn't

00:13:40.690 --> 00:13:43.120
survive our own dehumanizer.

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:44.640
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:44.640 --> 00:13:46.210
JAIME GREEN: But
even as all of that

00:13:46.210 --> 00:13:49.210
gets stripped away and
saved for future books,

00:13:49.210 --> 00:13:53.209
you have found kind of a
performance venue in your work

00:13:53.209 --> 00:13:55.000
in the Senate, which
is committee hearings.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:13:56.590
And it might not
have been that way

00:13:56.590 --> 00:13:58.750
if this weren't the
age of internet video.

00:13:58.750 --> 00:14:02.980
But I sat and watched
your questioning

00:14:02.980 --> 00:14:08.100
of Betsy DeVos and other cabinet
nominees and things like that.

00:14:08.100 --> 00:14:16.020
So it seems like that committee
work is really high-profile.

00:14:16.020 --> 00:14:18.340
How do you end up
on the committees

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:20.560
that you're on in the Senate?

00:14:20.560 --> 00:14:23.380
AL FRANKEN: The leader of your
party assigns you to them.

00:14:23.380 --> 00:14:26.805
And I had an eight
month process, a recount

00:14:26.805 --> 00:14:29.125
and a legal process,
so I got there last.

00:14:31.900 --> 00:14:33.910
So I got what
Harry had leftover.

00:14:33.910 --> 00:14:35.351
[LAUGHTER]

00:14:35.850 --> 00:14:42.220
And so I got judiciary.

00:14:42.220 --> 00:14:44.170
I asked for certain
committees and he said no,

00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:45.790
and then he told me what I had.

00:14:45.790 --> 00:14:48.460
And he said, you'd be
great in judiciary.

00:14:48.460 --> 00:14:51.460
And I said, I don't know if
you've noticed this, Harry,

00:14:51.460 --> 00:14:53.460
but there are a lot of
lawyers in the Senate.

00:14:53.460 --> 00:14:55.290
And I ain't one of them.

00:14:55.290 --> 00:15:01.500
And he said, that's
why you'd be great.

00:15:01.500 --> 00:15:04.920
And he was bullshitting.

00:15:04.920 --> 00:15:06.280
That's what he had.

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:07.960
So I'm on Judiciary.

00:15:07.960 --> 00:15:09.960
And I'm really happy I am.

00:15:09.960 --> 00:15:11.460
I'm really happy I am.

00:15:11.460 --> 00:15:13.380
I've done a lot of judiciary.

00:15:16.590 --> 00:15:22.000
And later, I got
what I did ask for,

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:24.450
which is the health committee--
health, education, labor,

00:15:24.450 --> 00:15:27.720
and pensions, which is not
that important unless you care

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:32.340
about your health or your
kid's health or your parents'

00:15:32.340 --> 00:15:35.895
health or their education
or your education.

00:15:35.895 --> 00:15:37.320
[LAUGHTER]

00:15:37.320 --> 00:15:40.680
Or if you plan to work
sometime during your life

00:15:40.680 --> 00:15:42.480
or maybe retire.

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:48.210
Other than that, it doesn't
have much, uh, jurisdiction.

00:15:48.210 --> 00:15:51.010
And then I'm on the
Energy Committee now.

00:15:51.010 --> 00:15:54.990
But at that time, I was
put on the Aging Committee.

00:15:54.990 --> 00:15:58.020
And Aging Committee is a
nonlegislative committee.

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:05.190
And I actually said
to Harry, aging?

00:16:05.190 --> 00:16:07.500
I mean, are people aging?

00:16:07.500 --> 00:16:10.485
And he didn't know
that I was kidding.

00:16:10.485 --> 00:16:12.540
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:12.540 --> 00:16:14.190
Harry's got a very
good sense of humor,

00:16:14.190 --> 00:16:15.870
but he didn't know me then.

00:16:15.870 --> 00:16:22.170
And so anyway, that's how you
get your committee assignments.

00:16:22.170 --> 00:16:24.090
That's the answer
to that question.

00:16:24.090 --> 00:16:25.800
[LAUGHTER]

00:16:25.800 --> 00:16:31.080
JAIME GREEN: And so with these
sort of hearings and sessions

00:16:31.080 --> 00:16:34.000
of questioning being put on
the internet and for everyone

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:34.800
to see them now--

00:16:34.800 --> 00:16:37.140
you don't have to sit at home
and watch C-SPAN in order

00:16:37.140 --> 00:16:39.094
to catch it--

00:16:39.094 --> 00:16:40.260
it can be very entertaining.

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:41.910
AL FRANKEN: And that's a
relief for everybody here

00:16:41.910 --> 00:16:43.050
who used to do that.

00:16:43.050 --> 00:16:43.883
JAIME GREEN: I know.

00:16:43.883 --> 00:16:46.300
It was really interfering
with their work, [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:46.300 --> 00:16:49.320
But they can be
very entertaining,

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:51.150
and certainly galvanizing.

00:16:51.150 --> 00:16:53.790
But I'm curious,
within the Senate,

00:16:53.790 --> 00:16:55.350
how those hearings function.

00:16:55.350 --> 00:16:56.850
Do they actually affect votes?

00:16:56.850 --> 00:17:00.944
What do you see the role of
those performances to be?

00:17:00.944 --> 00:17:03.110
AL FRANKEN: Well, I don't
consider it a performance.

00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:04.190
I consider it a hearing.

00:17:04.190 --> 00:17:06.390
And I consider a hearing
as a serious thing,

00:17:06.390 --> 00:17:09.540
where you're representing--

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:12.150
I'm representing the people of
Minnesota in those hearings,

00:17:12.150 --> 00:17:16.319
and I want to ask questions
I want the answers to.

00:17:16.319 --> 00:17:19.400
Sometimes the effect
of the hearing--

00:17:19.400 --> 00:17:24.599
we did not stop
people from-- like,

00:17:24.599 --> 00:17:28.440
we did not stop Betsy DeVos
from getting confirmed.

00:17:28.440 --> 00:17:30.750
The vice president, for
the first time in history,

00:17:30.750 --> 00:17:33.690
had to come down and cast
the tie-breaking vote

00:17:33.690 --> 00:17:35.850
to get her confirmed.

00:17:35.850 --> 00:17:42.750
But I felt that she did not
know education policy, which

00:17:42.750 --> 00:17:46.110
for the Secretary of Education
is an issue, I think.

00:17:46.110 --> 00:17:51.250
And so I demonstrated
that in my questioning.

00:17:51.250 --> 00:17:53.620
Sometimes the
questioning is something

00:17:53.620 --> 00:17:56.470
that exists for the record.

00:17:56.470 --> 00:18:03.090
In the judiciary hearings, I
asked Jeff Sessions a question

00:18:03.090 --> 00:18:08.160
that he responded to by
saying that he had not

00:18:08.160 --> 00:18:10.800
met with any Russians
during the campaign.

00:18:10.800 --> 00:18:14.280
That turned out not to be true.

00:18:14.280 --> 00:18:19.980
And he's under oath, and
that's a serious thing.

00:18:19.980 --> 00:18:22.740
But we didn't find that out till
well after he'd been confirmed.

00:18:22.740 --> 00:18:26.820
And there's some
news breaking today,

00:18:26.820 --> 00:18:30.690
possibly, about that,
about Senator Leahy and I,

00:18:30.690 --> 00:18:34.950
after we were not satisfied
with his answers about why

00:18:34.950 --> 00:18:40.590
he had not disclosed his
meetings with the Russians--

00:18:40.590 --> 00:18:44.910
which seems to be
something that there's

00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:50.790
a pattern of this, shall we say,
in the Trump administration.

00:18:50.790 --> 00:18:55.380
They aren't acting like people
who have nothing to hide.

00:18:55.380 --> 00:19:01.650
And because of his not
answering my question,

00:19:01.650 --> 00:19:04.620
or answering my question
in the way he did--

00:19:04.620 --> 00:19:07.785
not truthfully-- he ended
up recusing himself.

00:19:07.785 --> 00:19:11.170
And because he recused
himself, Rod Rosenstein,

00:19:11.170 --> 00:19:13.560
the Deputy Attorney
General, assigned

00:19:13.560 --> 00:19:15.342
the special
prosecutor, ultimately.

00:19:15.342 --> 00:19:17.300
And so that's why we have
a special prosecutor.

00:19:17.300 --> 00:19:22.010
So sometimes you do things
to get things on the record.

00:19:22.010 --> 00:19:23.260
JAIME GREEN: That makes sense.

00:19:23.260 --> 00:19:24.550
Yeah.

00:19:24.550 --> 00:19:30.650
So in the book, you
also write about being

00:19:30.650 --> 00:19:32.930
friends with many of your
Republican colleagues

00:19:32.930 --> 00:19:34.010
in the Senate.

00:19:34.010 --> 00:19:36.920
And you write about how
you're friends with them

00:19:36.920 --> 00:19:39.992
even though you vigorously
disagree with them.

00:19:39.992 --> 00:19:40.700
AL FRANKEN: Sure.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:42.241
JAIME GREEN: And I
would love to hear

00:19:42.241 --> 00:19:45.140
you talk about that a little,
because it seems like--

00:19:45.140 --> 00:19:48.420
it's not just, oh, I think
we should tax at 18%.

00:19:48.420 --> 00:19:50.150
I think we should tax at 14%.

00:19:50.150 --> 00:19:53.300
These are huge, almost
moral disagreements.

00:19:53.300 --> 00:19:58.026
And I think that it can be
very relevant to those of us

00:19:58.026 --> 00:19:59.900
not working in the Senate
too because they're

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:03.140
your colleagues, but some
of us have friends or family

00:20:03.140 --> 00:20:05.604
or colleagues with whom we
have these similar, very, very

00:20:05.604 --> 00:20:06.395
deep disagreements.

00:20:06.395 --> 00:20:08.690
So how do you maintain
those relationships?

00:20:08.690 --> 00:20:11.960
AL FRANKEN: Well,
we're a workplace.

00:20:11.960 --> 00:20:14.015
And you want to be
a good coworker.

00:20:18.260 --> 00:20:23.390
The way to get things done
in the Senate is to have--

00:20:23.390 --> 00:20:28.400
you're living in a town
that has 100 people in it,

00:20:28.400 --> 00:20:31.700
and your word has to be good.

00:20:31.700 --> 00:20:33.260
And that's more than anything.

00:20:33.260 --> 00:20:35.960
And I bonded with a
number of Republicans

00:20:35.960 --> 00:20:39.230
right away just with humor.

00:20:41.930 --> 00:20:45.830
Jim DeMint, a very
right-wing senator

00:20:45.830 --> 00:20:47.840
at the time from
South Carolina-- now

00:20:47.840 --> 00:20:49.714
he's head of the
Heritage Foundation--

00:20:49.714 --> 00:20:51.380
came up to me on the
floor the first day

00:20:51.380 --> 00:20:55.584
I was there and said, how
are things on the far left?

00:20:55.584 --> 00:20:56.500
I said, they're great.

00:20:56.500 --> 00:20:58.310
How are things on
the nutcase right?

00:20:58.310 --> 00:20:59.270
[LAUGHTER]

00:20:59.270 --> 00:21:02.900
And he laughed, and we
continued having a relationship

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:04.400
while he was in
the Senate, based

00:21:04.400 --> 00:21:06.920
on just giving each other crap.

00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:10.550
But it was a good relationship.

00:21:10.550 --> 00:21:14.540
Lindsey Graham is really funny.

00:21:14.540 --> 00:21:19.370
When he was like 16th out of
17 in the presidential race,

00:21:19.370 --> 00:21:22.070
I went up to him
and said, you know,

00:21:22.070 --> 00:21:26.300
Lindsey, if I were voting
in the Republican primaries,

00:21:26.300 --> 00:21:27.124
I'd vote for you.

00:21:27.124 --> 00:21:28.415
And he said, that's my problem.

00:21:28.415 --> 00:21:30.870
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:32.820 --> 00:21:38.580
Now, I have one
colleague, Tom Coburn,

00:21:38.580 --> 00:21:43.360
who didn't seem to have
any sense of humor.

00:21:43.360 --> 00:21:46.950
So my first four or
five exchanges with him

00:21:46.950 --> 00:21:47.650
were not good.

00:21:47.650 --> 00:21:50.419
And I went up to him.

00:21:50.419 --> 00:21:51.960
I said, Tom, can I
take you to lunch?

00:21:51.960 --> 00:21:53.790
He said, tell you what.

00:21:53.790 --> 00:21:55.650
Take me to breakfast.

00:21:55.650 --> 00:22:00.210
And Tom was kind
of called Dr. No,

00:22:00.210 --> 00:22:04.380
because he was a medical doctor
before he went into the Senate,

00:22:04.380 --> 00:22:12.540
and he also was very,
very big on spending.

00:22:12.540 --> 00:22:14.400
He wanted to balance the budget.

00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:16.590
And he said no to
a lot of things,

00:22:16.590 --> 00:22:23.010
and used his privileges
to stop a lot of stuff.

00:22:23.010 --> 00:22:25.905
So we go to breakfast
the next day.

00:22:28.377 --> 00:22:30.210
At the beginning of
breakfast I said, look--

00:22:30.210 --> 00:22:31.584
we're in the Senate
dining room--

00:22:31.584 --> 00:22:34.490
I said, over the
next 45 minutes,

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:35.704
we can talk about anything.

00:22:35.704 --> 00:22:37.870
We can talk about politics,
talk about our families,

00:22:37.870 --> 00:22:41.070
talk about our
careers before here.

00:22:41.070 --> 00:22:42.480
But let's have fun, OK?

00:22:42.480 --> 00:22:44.160
He goes, OK, let's have fun.

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:45.730
We'll have fun.

00:22:45.730 --> 00:22:50.770
So I said, OK, now,
let's talk about careers.

00:22:50.770 --> 00:22:53.970
You were a doctor
before you came here.

00:22:53.970 --> 00:22:55.110
Let me ask you something.

00:22:55.110 --> 00:22:59.820
To be a doctor in
Oklahoma, do you have

00:22:59.820 --> 00:23:02.340
to have any formal education?

00:23:02.340 --> 00:23:05.532
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:06.922 --> 00:23:08.380
And he said,
[SHOUTING] yes, you've

00:23:08.380 --> 00:23:09.970
got to go to medical school.

00:23:09.970 --> 00:23:11.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:11.170 --> 00:23:16.090
And I said, OK, that was a joke.

00:23:16.090 --> 00:23:21.370
You see, that's what
I did for my career.

00:23:21.370 --> 00:23:24.670
And then we had a delightful
breakfast in which

00:23:24.670 --> 00:23:26.230
I taught him what jokes were--

00:23:26.230 --> 00:23:27.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:23:27.400 --> 00:23:29.581
--and what proper response was.

00:23:29.581 --> 00:23:31.330
And he wrote me a note
afterwards and said

00:23:31.330 --> 00:23:33.670
he had a delightful breakfast.

00:23:33.670 --> 00:23:35.060
And we got along really well.

00:23:35.060 --> 00:23:37.310
And so I write
about Ted Cruz, who

00:23:37.310 --> 00:23:41.590
seems to be the
exception to the rule.

00:23:41.590 --> 00:23:42.475
JAIME GREEN: Yeah.

00:23:42.475 --> 00:23:44.600
We're going to open it up
to questions in a minute,

00:23:44.600 --> 00:23:46.960
so if you have a
question, you can line up

00:23:46.960 --> 00:23:49.030
at one of the microphones.

00:23:49.030 --> 00:23:51.430
But I want to ask
one more question.

00:23:51.430 --> 00:23:56.290
So you point out in the book
that once President Obama was

00:23:56.290 --> 00:23:58.330
elected, the Republican
plan in Congress

00:23:58.330 --> 00:24:00.370
just became obstruction.

00:24:00.370 --> 00:24:02.860
Stop him from getting
anything done.

00:24:02.860 --> 00:24:07.210
And that hasn't changed.

00:24:07.210 --> 00:24:08.885
They still are trying
to stop anything--

00:24:08.885 --> 00:24:10.510
AL FRANKEN: No, I
mean, it has changed.

00:24:10.510 --> 00:24:12.010
We have a different
from President.

00:24:15.100 --> 00:24:18.950
Mitch McConnell said something
that kind of shocked me.

00:24:18.950 --> 00:24:23.710
He said, our number one goal is
to see to it that Barack Obama

00:24:23.710 --> 00:24:25.460
is a one-term president.

00:24:25.460 --> 00:24:27.160
And I wasn't shocked
that he thought

00:24:27.160 --> 00:24:29.650
that but I was shocked that
he said it out loud, because I

00:24:29.650 --> 00:24:34.660
think our number one goal should
be to improve people's lives,

00:24:34.660 --> 00:24:38.140
to provide a world-class
education to our kids,

00:24:38.140 --> 00:24:41.650
to make sure that our
economy is working,

00:24:41.650 --> 00:24:46.580
to make sure that veterans
get the care they need.

00:24:46.580 --> 00:24:49.810
There's a lot of
things that must

00:24:49.810 --> 00:24:52.900
come before partisan politics.

00:24:52.900 --> 00:24:54.880
So I was shocked about that.

00:24:54.880 --> 00:24:57.790
But he used the
rules of the Senate

00:24:57.790 --> 00:25:02.830
to try to stop Barack Obama
from having any achievements.

00:25:02.830 --> 00:25:07.120
And I have a chapter called
"The Great Curdling."

00:25:07.120 --> 00:25:11.710
And things curdled during
that period and got very bad.

00:25:11.710 --> 00:25:14.710
When I first got
there, it was bad.

00:25:14.710 --> 00:25:19.070
And I asked a colleague who had
been there for about 30 years,

00:25:19.070 --> 00:25:20.410
I said, was it always this bad?

00:25:20.410 --> 00:25:22.180
No, no, no, no.

00:25:22.180 --> 00:25:24.820
I said, has it ever
been worse than this?

00:25:24.820 --> 00:25:26.780
Oh, yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:30.040
Remember when that
guy got caned?

00:25:30.040 --> 00:25:34.570
And I said, Charles Sumner
who got caned like right

00:25:34.570 --> 00:25:35.445
before the Civil War?

00:25:35.445 --> 00:25:36.970
And he goes, yeah,
that was worse.

00:25:36.970 --> 00:25:37.759
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:37.759 --> 00:25:38.425
JAIME GREEN: OK.

00:25:38.425 --> 00:25:41.335
That's reassuring.

00:25:41.335 --> 00:25:42.305
AL FRANKEN: Yeah.

00:25:42.305 --> 00:25:45.940
[LAUGHTER]

00:25:46.440 --> 00:25:50.470
So you write in the book,
by the time you read this,

00:25:50.470 --> 00:25:51.940
Republicans may
well have succeeded

00:25:51.940 --> 00:25:54.530
in repealing some or all
of the Affordable Care Act.

00:25:54.530 --> 00:25:56.530
But I'm willing to bet
they won't have succeeded

00:25:56.530 --> 00:25:58.974
in replacing it, because
the truth is they've never

00:25:58.974 --> 00:26:01.390
been interested in addressing
the central challenge, which

00:26:01.390 --> 00:26:04.160
I think applies sort of
broadly to that curdling.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:08.020
So if they're not trying to
pass legislation that will

00:26:08.020 --> 00:26:10.900
improve or replace Obamacare--

00:26:10.900 --> 00:26:14.200
AL FRANKEN: This is the
thing about the book.

00:26:14.200 --> 00:26:17.590
We did education together
in the health committee.

00:26:17.590 --> 00:26:20.530
And Lamar Alexander was
very good in that process.

00:26:20.530 --> 00:26:24.640
And it took us a while, but
we ultimately passed a bill

00:26:24.640 --> 00:26:26.590
that we all were happy with.

00:26:26.590 --> 00:26:28.130
And we can do it.

00:26:28.130 --> 00:26:29.530
So it depends on the issue.

00:26:29.530 --> 00:26:33.430
But on health
care, I don't think

00:26:33.430 --> 00:26:37.340
the Republicans thought Donald
Trump would become president.

00:26:37.340 --> 00:26:40.360
They assumed Hillary would
be and they could still

00:26:40.360 --> 00:26:46.045
continue to use Obamacare
just as a political bludgeon.

00:26:50.250 --> 00:26:53.650
And I don't think
that they have given--

00:26:53.650 --> 00:26:58.090
Donald Trump said
that nobody knew

00:26:58.090 --> 00:27:01.150
that health care was
complicated until he figured out

00:27:01.150 --> 00:27:03.470
that it was complicated.

00:27:03.470 --> 00:27:06.910
It's very complex, our
health care system.

00:27:06.910 --> 00:27:12.220
And I don't think that many
of my Republican colleagues--

00:27:12.220 --> 00:27:15.640
and I know this for sure,
because I've talked to many

00:27:15.640 --> 00:27:16.510
of them--

00:27:16.510 --> 00:27:22.900
have really thought through what
to replace the Affordable Care

00:27:22.900 --> 00:27:23.907
Act with.

00:27:23.907 --> 00:27:25.240
That's what I was writing about.

00:27:25.240 --> 00:27:28.405
And of course, we're
seeing a process

00:27:28.405 --> 00:27:31.540
that I think is the wrong
process in the Senate right

00:27:31.540 --> 00:27:36.720
now, where 13 Republicans
are behind closed doors.

00:27:36.720 --> 00:27:37.960
They're not currently.

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:40.240
They're in recess.

00:27:40.240 --> 00:27:47.500
But they're trying to
come up with something.

00:27:47.500 --> 00:27:48.610
We should be doing this.

00:27:48.610 --> 00:27:49.972
There should be an open process.

00:27:49.972 --> 00:27:52.180
We should be doing it like
we did the Affordable Care

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:54.492
Act, through committees.

00:27:54.492 --> 00:27:55.450
JAIME GREEN: All right.

00:27:55.450 --> 00:27:58.054
We're going to open it
up to questions now.

00:27:58.054 --> 00:27:58.990
AUDIENCE: Hi, Senator.

00:27:58.990 --> 00:27:59.890
Thank you for coming.

00:27:59.890 --> 00:28:00.980
AL FRANKEN: Sure, thank you.

00:28:00.980 --> 00:28:03.646
AUDIENCE: I imagine you probably
get this question all the time,

00:28:03.646 --> 00:28:05.940
but for people who
are not politics

00:28:05.940 --> 00:28:11.530
are going in the US right
now, what can we do about it?

00:28:11.530 --> 00:28:16.875
AL FRANKEN: If you're
not happy, get involved.

00:28:16.875 --> 00:28:17.375
Get engaged.

00:28:21.020 --> 00:28:25.160
Throwing your hands up and
saying things are terrible

00:28:25.160 --> 00:28:30.980
is not a way to make
our system work better.

00:28:30.980 --> 00:28:37.820
It just leaves it to the people
who are cynical and don't care.

00:28:37.820 --> 00:28:46.170
So I am very much heartened by
the reaction that we've had.

00:28:46.170 --> 00:28:51.320
The Women's March on Washington
was an amazing event.

00:28:51.320 --> 00:28:56.510
And people going to town
hall meetings, I think,

00:28:56.510 --> 00:29:01.160
helped defeat the
House health care

00:29:01.160 --> 00:29:06.650
bills that were the predecessor
to this horrible bill.

00:29:06.650 --> 00:29:13.200
But get involved in
an advocacy group.

00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:18.400
If you care about
mental health, then

