00:31:08.590 --> 00:31:09.520
to be on offense.

00:31:09.520 --> 00:31:11.050
We're on offense
in our messaging.

00:31:11.050 --> 00:31:13.300
We're on offense in many ways.

00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:17.200
But we are in the
minority in both houses,

00:31:17.200 --> 00:31:22.045
and the White House is
controlled by Donald Trump's

00:31:22.045 --> 00:31:23.390
the president.

00:31:23.390 --> 00:31:25.420
So we--

00:31:25.420 --> 00:31:28.120
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:28.825 --> 00:31:30.220
I try to play offense.

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:32.711
I try to play offense
in the hearings.

00:31:32.711 --> 00:31:34.752
AUDIENCE: Are there
cooridnated efforts, thougth?

00:31:34.752 --> 00:31:37.608
Because I see you
playing offense,

00:31:37.608 --> 00:31:41.529
and I see Senator Warren and
Keith Ellison playing offense.

00:31:41.529 --> 00:31:43.320
But are there coordinated
efforts to do so?

00:31:43.320 --> 00:31:45.900
AL FRANKEN: Yeah.

00:31:45.900 --> 00:31:49.482
Democrats sometimes have
problems with messaging.

00:31:49.482 --> 00:31:51.690
The way I like to put it--
and I put it in the book--

00:31:51.690 --> 00:31:54.810
is that our bumper
stickers always and with,

00:31:54.810 --> 00:31:56.700
continued on next
bumper sticker.

00:31:56.700 --> 00:31:58.484
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:59.960 --> 00:32:02.500
I mean, it's not like we're
not trying, believe me.

00:32:05.030 --> 00:32:07.970
We're trying to be on
offense at all times.

00:32:07.970 --> 00:32:10.947
AUDIENCE: If that's the problem,
what are you doing to fix it?

00:32:10.947 --> 00:32:12.780
AL FRANKEN: What am I
going to do to fix it?

00:32:12.780 --> 00:32:22.470
I can only-- I myself am
doing my job the best I can,

00:32:22.470 --> 00:32:26.100
and I'm being as aggressive as
I can when it's appropriate.

00:32:26.100 --> 00:32:36.110
And in this book, I write
about victories that matter,

00:32:36.110 --> 00:32:38.960
that matter in people's lives.

00:32:38.960 --> 00:32:43.470
My first bill, I passed two
weeks after I got to Congress--

00:32:43.470 --> 00:32:49.010
my co-sponsor, Johnny Isakson,
a Republican from Georgia--

00:32:49.010 --> 00:32:53.090
was to get service
dogs to veterans

00:32:53.090 --> 00:32:56.780
from Iraq and
Afghanistan who have PTSD

00:32:56.780 --> 00:33:00.020
and traumatic brain injury
and other invisible wounds,

00:33:00.020 --> 00:33:05.010
because these dogs
help them tremendously.

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:08.030
And that is, to me--

00:33:08.030 --> 00:33:14.180
I've gotten increased funding
for mental health in schools.

00:33:14.180 --> 00:33:19.010
That is an enormous victory for
me that I really care about.

00:33:21.830 --> 00:33:23.700
I'm on the offensive,
believe me.

00:33:23.700 --> 00:33:26.480
And we are on the offensive
on this health care

00:33:26.480 --> 00:33:28.640
bill, this terrible,
awful health care

00:33:28.640 --> 00:33:33.980
bill that has an $880 billion
cut in Medicaid-- which,

00:33:33.980 --> 00:33:37.670
the president said he
would never cut Medicaid.

00:33:37.670 --> 00:33:40.070
We're pointing that out.

00:33:40.070 --> 00:33:44.180
And people are freaked out
about it in rural Minnesota.

00:33:44.180 --> 00:33:45.420
I can tell you that.

00:33:45.420 --> 00:33:46.670
And all over Minnesota.

00:33:46.670 --> 00:33:49.820
But I'm Co-Chair of the
Rural Health Caucus,

00:33:49.820 --> 00:33:51.680
so I go all around
rural Minnesota.

00:33:51.680 --> 00:33:53.720
I'm on the offense.

00:33:53.720 --> 00:33:56.540
I'm doing the best I can.

00:33:56.540 --> 00:33:58.730
Chuck Schumer is
doing the best we can.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:00.950
Tom Perez is doing
the best he can.

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:03.530
We will fall short and
disappoint you all the time.

00:34:03.530 --> 00:34:06.701
[LAUGHTER]

00:34:07.137 --> 00:34:07.970
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

00:34:07.970 --> 00:34:08.886
AL FRANKEN: Thank you.

00:34:08.886 --> 00:34:10.309
AUDIENCE: Thank you, senator.

00:34:10.309 --> 00:34:13.489
If you look at different
types of charts--

00:34:13.489 --> 00:34:15.290
if you look at charts
of income inequality,

00:34:15.290 --> 00:34:17.719
if you look at
charts that examine

00:34:17.719 --> 00:34:23.246
congressional legislation
compared to public opinion,

00:34:23.246 --> 00:34:24.620
and most importantly,
if you look

00:34:24.620 --> 00:34:30.710
at statistical data of outcomes
of congressional campaigns

00:34:30.710 --> 00:34:33.290
and congressional elections
versus the amount of money

00:34:33.290 --> 00:34:37.370
spent on the campaigns,
our democracy

00:34:37.370 --> 00:34:39.889
resembles more of an oligarchy.

00:34:39.889 --> 00:34:42.510
If you can say, as
you can in the States,

00:34:42.510 --> 00:34:45.380
that you can pretty much
predict with high accuracy

00:34:45.380 --> 00:34:48.500
the outcome of an election
based on the money spent on it,

00:34:48.500 --> 00:34:51.409
it's hard to claim that
this is a democracy,

00:34:51.409 --> 00:34:54.050
because the people's
opinion clearly matters

00:34:54.050 --> 00:34:57.290
much less than the money spent.

00:34:57.290 --> 00:35:00.880
Given that, it seems like
our democratic process

00:35:00.880 --> 00:35:04.080
is running with its hands
tied behind its back.

00:35:06.956 --> 00:35:10.550
How can we achieve
anything significant

00:35:10.550 --> 00:35:14.510
before we address this very
serious problem of campaign

00:35:14.510 --> 00:35:16.260
financing?

00:35:16.260 --> 00:35:21.140
And why do we not hear more
about this from Congress?

00:35:24.550 --> 00:35:26.710
AL FRANKEN: You know,
one of the worst

00:35:26.710 --> 00:35:32.200
parts of having Donald Trump
as president instead of Hillary

00:35:32.200 --> 00:35:35.890
Clinton is who they--

00:35:35.890 --> 00:35:43.300
we have Neil Gorsuch now
as the ninth justice.

00:35:43.300 --> 00:35:45.370
I was hoping that
Hillary would win--

00:35:45.370 --> 00:35:48.830
I fought very hard for her--

00:35:48.830 --> 00:35:50.890
so that we would
get a justice who

00:35:50.890 --> 00:35:54.580
would overturn
Citizens United, which

00:35:54.580 --> 00:36:02.410
is one of the most pernicious
decisions we've seen.

00:36:02.410 --> 00:36:06.370
It's interesting that Justice
Kennedy wrote the majority

00:36:06.370 --> 00:36:07.210
opinion in that.

00:36:07.210 --> 00:36:09.700
He said, this doesn't
present even the appearance

00:36:09.700 --> 00:36:10.360
of corruption.

00:36:10.360 --> 00:36:11.602
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:12.430 --> 00:36:16.360
And he said that
because of the internet,

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:21.640
everyone will be able to
see who gave what to whom.

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:24.610
He envisioned, and their
decision envisioned,

00:36:24.610 --> 00:36:26.320
disclosure.

00:36:26.320 --> 00:36:28.690
And we tried to get
disclosure done.

00:36:28.690 --> 00:36:32.600
And every Republican
voted against it.

00:36:32.600 --> 00:36:36.700
At that point, we had 15--
this is after Scott Brown had

00:36:36.700 --> 00:36:39.790
won in Massachusetts.

00:36:39.790 --> 00:36:42.640
They needed 41 and they had 41.

00:36:46.570 --> 00:36:49.780
You're absolutely
right about this.

00:36:49.780 --> 00:36:56.510
I mean, you can say that
Hillary spent more than Trump.

00:36:56.510 --> 00:36:58.660
And that was the big one.

00:36:58.660 --> 00:37:04.600
He got a lot of free
media, because people

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:07.270
were entertained by him.

00:37:07.270 --> 00:37:10.270
But you're right.

00:37:10.270 --> 00:37:12.200
There's a book that
Sheldon Whitehouse

00:37:12.200 --> 00:37:14.870
has written called
"Captured," which

00:37:14.870 --> 00:37:22.640
talks about how big corporations
and big special interests

00:37:22.640 --> 00:37:25.020
have captured a
number of things--

00:37:25.020 --> 00:37:31.980
including, through campaign
finance stuff, our elections--

00:37:31.980 --> 00:37:34.040
the ability for people
to get in the court.

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:40.600
Our regulatory agencies
sometimes get captured.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:42.335
The courts are captured.

00:37:45.800 --> 00:37:46.970
It's a problem.

00:37:46.970 --> 00:37:51.344
One thing I can say is that
most Americans agree with you.

00:37:51.344 --> 00:37:53.260
The vast majority of
Americans agree with you.

00:37:53.260 --> 00:37:57.140
But if you ask them, what's the
most important issue to you?

00:37:57.140 --> 00:37:59.560
It comes out eighth
or ninth or tenth.

00:37:59.560 --> 00:38:03.880
It is an existential threat.

00:38:03.880 --> 00:38:05.800
AUDIENCE: It should be first.

00:38:05.800 --> 00:38:09.010
So who's championing
this in the Senate?

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:16.910
AL FRANKEN: Well, we are
fighting for reform and losing.

00:38:16.910 --> 00:38:19.210
But it's people like
Sheldon Whitehouse.

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:21.170
It's people like--

00:38:21.170 --> 00:38:22.720
I've been in this fight.

00:38:22.720 --> 00:38:25.810
It's been Elizabeth
Warren, Bernie.

00:38:25.810 --> 00:38:30.910
I mean, Dick Durbin has always
led for public financing

00:38:30.910 --> 00:38:31.690
of elections.

00:38:31.690 --> 00:38:33.100
And I agree with that.

00:38:33.100 --> 00:38:37.330
I've been a co-sponsor of
his legislation to do that.

00:38:37.330 --> 00:38:40.170
We just don't have--

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:42.190
the Republican Party
will not do this.

00:38:42.190 --> 00:38:49.265
So right now, we are
not winning that one.

00:38:49.265 --> 00:38:50.666
JAIME GREEN: OK, thanks.

00:38:50.666 --> 00:38:51.600
Over here?

00:38:51.600 --> 00:38:52.534
AUDIENCE: Hi, senator.

00:38:52.534 --> 00:38:53.470
Thanks for coming.

00:38:53.470 --> 00:38:57.292
You mentioned that you work with
a lot of lawyers in Congress.

00:38:57.292 --> 00:39:00.890
And I'm wondering if you think
that lawyers and prosecutors

00:39:00.890 --> 00:39:06.170
in particular are more
qualified to serve in Congress,

00:39:06.170 --> 00:39:09.770
or if perhaps lawyers are
sort of more accommodating

00:39:09.770 --> 00:39:13.880
of doublespeak and dishonesty
that I think frustrates

00:39:13.880 --> 00:39:15.020
us in politics.

00:39:15.020 --> 00:39:16.760
[LAUGHTER]

00:39:16.760 --> 00:39:20.915
AL FRANKEN: Well, a lot of
my colleagues are lawyers.

00:39:23.470 --> 00:39:26.150
And there's colleagues
that I admire tremendously

00:39:26.150 --> 00:39:28.760
who are lawyers, and
there are colleagues

00:39:28.760 --> 00:39:33.710
that I don't admire
tremendously who are lawyers.

00:39:33.710 --> 00:39:37.850
I think probably when Harry said
I'd be good on the committee

00:39:37.850 --> 00:39:39.890
because I'm not a
lawyer, I actually

00:39:39.890 --> 00:39:45.560
think that I play
a good role there.

00:39:45.560 --> 00:39:47.420
I think my training
as a satirist--

00:39:51.200 --> 00:39:53.780
I can spot inconsistencies.

00:39:53.780 --> 00:39:58.909
Satirists are trained in
a certain kind of way.

00:39:58.909 --> 00:40:00.950
And because of the books
I wrote, "Lies and Lying

00:40:00.950 --> 00:40:06.050
Liars Who Tell Them,"
[INAUDIBLE], or "Rush Limbaugh

00:40:06.050 --> 00:40:09.110
is a Big Fat Idiot and
Other Observations,"

00:40:09.110 --> 00:40:16.940
all very high-minded books
of satire, trained me.

00:40:16.940 --> 00:40:20.120
And that's why I think I've had
a high profile in my hearings,

00:40:20.120 --> 00:40:23.690
because I think I
know how to frame

00:40:23.690 --> 00:40:26.090
things because of
my training and know

00:40:26.090 --> 00:40:27.920
how to make something land.

00:40:27.920 --> 00:40:36.290
So we are making the laws, so
being a lawyer has its upside.

00:40:36.290 --> 00:40:37.970
But I think you're
right, I'd like

00:40:37.970 --> 00:40:40.220
to see people who
aren't lawyers.

00:40:40.220 --> 00:40:43.190
By the way, I want to just
say one thing very quickly.

00:40:43.190 --> 00:40:45.809
And I maybe shouldn't
be so quick about this.

00:40:45.809 --> 00:40:47.600
But I write it in the
book, because there's

00:40:47.600 --> 00:40:54.160
a lot of despair
hanging on the room.

00:40:54.160 --> 00:40:55.670
There's hope here.

00:40:55.670 --> 00:41:02.340
In 2004, we lost the White House
in a very, very close election.

00:41:02.340 --> 00:41:07.930
And George W. Bush,
I think by then,

00:41:07.930 --> 00:41:11.510
it was apparent that we had
really been lied into the war,

00:41:11.510 --> 00:41:14.300
that they had made the
decision to go to war

00:41:14.300 --> 00:41:16.970
and then kind of cooked
the books and the evidence

00:41:16.970 --> 00:41:18.390
to get us there.

00:41:18.390 --> 00:41:20.890
And that was a very
difficult defeat.

00:41:20.890 --> 00:41:23.150
But we came back.

00:41:23.150 --> 00:41:26.430
And it was because of things
like Air America, which

00:41:26.430 --> 00:41:27.620
I was a radio host for.

00:41:27.620 --> 00:41:31.820
It was things like
Media Matters, which

00:41:31.820 --> 00:41:34.190
answered the
right-wing messaging

00:41:34.190 --> 00:41:37.220
machine in a very
effective way, the Center

00:41:37.220 --> 00:41:41.580
for American Progress, a
progressive think tank.

00:41:41.580 --> 00:41:44.240
And in '06, we took
the Congress back.

00:41:44.240 --> 00:41:48.710
And in '08, we had Barack
Obama win the White House.

00:41:48.710 --> 00:41:54.370
And we had for a moment, for
a couple of months, 60 votes.

00:41:54.370 --> 00:41:59.370
So don't despair.

00:41:59.370 --> 00:42:01.959
Get active is what I'm saying.

