AUDIENCE: In terms of advocacy
and what we care about,

00:50:14.300 --> 00:50:16.940
you could say a few
people in this room care

00:50:16.940 --> 00:50:19.240
a little bit about the
quality of information

00:50:19.240 --> 00:50:22.700
and how it's delivered.

00:50:22.700 --> 00:50:24.130
AL FRANKEN: Thank god.

00:50:24.130 --> 00:50:25.830
If you guys didn't, who would?

00:50:28.790 --> 00:50:32.450
AUDIENCE: There's a lot
of noise between all

00:50:32.450 --> 00:50:38.945
of the information out there and
how it gets to everyday people.

00:50:38.945 --> 00:50:43.460
And I'm very interested
to find out from you

00:50:43.460 --> 00:50:46.220
how you cut through all that.

00:50:46.220 --> 00:50:53.190
And which medium have you found
to be the most clearcut channel

00:50:53.190 --> 00:50:56.640
to get directly from what
you want to communicate

00:50:56.640 --> 00:50:58.380
to your constituents?

00:50:58.380 --> 00:51:02.585
Because I've seen how you've
done it through humor and books

00:51:02.585 --> 00:51:03.210
over the years.

00:51:03.210 --> 00:51:07.890
And on a personal note, what you
did on Air America radio with

00:51:07.890 --> 00:51:11.420
Janeane Garofalo-- and Rachel
Maddow was on right before

00:51:11.420 --> 00:51:11.920
you--

00:51:11.920 --> 00:51:15.230
that helped me
connect as a citizen.

00:51:15.230 --> 00:51:18.330
I was right out of college, just
started in the tech industry.

00:51:18.330 --> 00:51:19.836
And in terms of--

00:51:19.836 --> 00:51:22.500
I home-schooled myself and
went to community college

00:51:22.500 --> 00:51:24.960
and went to college, and
now I work at Google.

00:51:24.960 --> 00:51:28.760
20 years later-- it's my
20-year reunion this year--

00:51:28.760 --> 00:51:32.090
I now can afford to pay off my
student loans, 20 years later.

00:51:32.090 --> 00:51:34.970
I'm doing it this year in
honor of my 20-year reunion.

00:51:34.970 --> 00:51:38.040
The things that you connected
to me through radio,

00:51:38.040 --> 00:51:40.830
through just an
audio channel alone,

00:51:40.830 --> 00:51:42.960
felt like an audience
of one to me,

00:51:42.960 --> 00:51:47.040
like I got the most
as a citizen from you,

00:51:47.040 --> 00:51:48.750
and you weren't
even a senator yet.

00:51:48.750 --> 00:51:52.960
So now, as a senator, you speak
directly to your constituents,

00:51:52.960 --> 00:51:53.460
I imagine.

00:51:53.460 --> 00:51:56.964
You also speak through
the dehumanizer.

00:51:56.964 --> 00:51:58.380
What's the most
effective channel,

00:51:58.380 --> 00:52:02.160
and how do you connect with
your constituents the most

00:52:02.160 --> 00:52:06.510
and how do you cut
through all that?

00:52:06.510 --> 00:52:12.800
AL FRANKEN: Ed, my
communications chief, is here.

00:52:12.800 --> 00:52:15.780
We try to use any tool we can.

00:52:15.780 --> 00:52:17.015
We try to use social media.

00:52:21.020 --> 00:52:25.460
I try to do it when
I have a platform.

00:52:25.460 --> 00:52:30.620
And if I have a platform
in a hearing, I use it.

00:52:30.620 --> 00:52:32.270
Floor speeches.

00:52:32.270 --> 00:52:35.615
Speeches-- hopefully this
is going to reach people.

00:52:39.600 --> 00:52:42.990
This is why net
neutrality, to me,

00:52:42.990 --> 00:52:48.540
is a huge First
Amendment issue, and why

00:52:48.540 --> 00:52:51.810
I believe that
people have to fight

00:52:51.810 --> 00:52:56.460
what the FCC is
trying to reverse,

00:52:56.460 --> 00:52:58.350
the open internet rule.

00:52:58.350 --> 00:53:03.160
And I think this is
very, very dangerous.

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:07.200
We've always had net
neutrality on the internet.

00:53:07.200 --> 00:53:09.210
And it's from the
very beginning,

00:53:09.210 --> 00:53:13.830
when it was the arpanet--

00:53:13.830 --> 00:53:19.200
I'm sorry, when
DARPA had started it,

00:53:19.200 --> 00:53:27.070
we need to preserve that
so that all information is

00:53:27.070 --> 00:53:28.570
treated equally.

00:53:28.570 --> 00:53:30.860
I think that's
absolutely essential.

00:53:30.860 --> 00:53:33.480
And we can't have huge
corporate interests,

00:53:33.480 --> 00:53:35.770
and especially internet
service providers,

00:53:35.770 --> 00:53:39.280
deciding what information
gets to flow free

00:53:39.280 --> 00:53:42.940
and what you have to
pay for, et cetera.

00:53:42.940 --> 00:53:47.230
So again, it's also
an existential issue.

00:53:47.230 --> 00:53:49.150
We have many
existential issues--

00:53:49.150 --> 00:53:54.340
campaign finance
reform, net neutrality,

00:53:54.340 --> 00:53:55.770
climate change for God's sakes.

00:54:00.180 --> 00:54:01.810
We haven't discussed that.

00:54:01.810 --> 00:54:06.750
We're at Google, so we
should be discussing this.

00:54:06.750 --> 00:54:09.090
So that's one thing I've
been leading the charge on,

00:54:09.090 --> 00:54:11.760
is net neutrality.

00:54:11.760 --> 00:54:15.690
I try to get my message
out any way I can.

00:54:15.690 --> 00:54:20.490
And if you have anybody here
that can help us, let us know.

00:54:20.490 --> 00:54:21.360
OK?

00:54:21.360 --> 00:54:22.020
Thank you.

00:54:22.020 --> 00:54:23.700
